#### W-6: Workplace Safety
*Strategy:* Assert + Navigate
*See also:* W-2: Understanding Your Rights If You're Let Go (if retaliation follows), L-3: Writing a Demand Letter
*My Man Jeeves:* _One's body is, if one may be permitted the observation, the asset one brings to work. The employer's obligation not to damage it is codified in law, implemented through OSHA, and enforced through a system that requires the worker to know it exists and how to employ it. Workers' compensation is insurance the employer is required to carry. Filing a claim is not an adversarial act — it is the use of the system as designed. The adversarial dimension, one regrets to note, tends to present itself later, should the claim be denied, and it is denied with a frequency that warrants preparation. One's Agent has read the relevant OSHA regulations and can assist with both the filing and the appeal._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I have a workplace safety concern [or: I was injured at work].
My situation: [describe — unsafe conditions, injury type, when it
happened, what I've reported so far]
My state: [state]
My employer's response so far: [cooperative / dismissive /
retaliatory / I haven't reported yet]
Please help me:
1. Understand my rights under OSHA and state worker's comp law
2. Walk me through the reporting and filing process step by step
3. Tell me what deadlines I cannot miss
4. Explain what protections I have against retaliation —
   and be honest about how strong those protections actually are
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Document everything. Photograph conditions. Save communications. If you are injured, report to your employer in writing, seek medical attention, and file a workers' comp claim — in that order, and the first 24 hours set the trajectory of the entire case. Your state's workers' comp board website has the specific filing forms and deadlines.

::: fairness
Workers in high-risk industries — construction, agriculture, warehousing, meatpacking — have the highest injury rates and the least bargaining power to demand improvements. If your Agent's advice assumes a white-collar office, specify your actual work environment.
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: OSHA enforcement capacity. OSHA has approximately 1,850 inspectors for 8 million workplaces in the United States. At current staffing, it would take 165 years to inspect each workplace once (AFL-CIO "Death on the Job" report — verify latest year). This is not a conspiracy. It is a budget. The practical implication: OSHA is reactive, not proactive. Your complaint triggers the inspection. Without your complaint, conditions persist. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The fear of reporting unsafe conditions — retaliation, ostracism, being labeled a troublemaker, losing overtime — is the primary barrier to workplace safety. This is a social-psychological problem masquerading as a legal one. The legal protections exist on paper. The social cost of being "that person" is real, daily, and unaddressed by the statute. The entry should acknowledge this honestly. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Workers' comp denial rates and appeals process. Similar dynamic to health insurance denials (H-4): the initial denial is often a business decision, not a medical one. Appeal success rates are significant when workers actually appeal. The information asymmetry — not the merits — is the barrier. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The intersection of immigration status and workplace safety is one of the most cynical information asymmetries in American labor. Undocumented workers have the highest workplace fatality rates (particularly in construction and agriculture) and the lowest reporting rates. OSHA protections technically apply regardless of immigration status, but the practical reality is that reporting an unsafe workplace can trigger immigration consequences. The workers most at risk are the least able to use the safety system designed to protect them. The entry should name this. -->

